  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>Let $P(z)=z^3+(1+j) z^2+(2+j) z+3$, where $z$ is complex number. Which one of the following is true?</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "<p>Conjugate $\\{P(z)\\}=P$ (Conjugate $\\{z\\}$ ) for all $z$</p>\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "<p>The sum of the roots of $P(z)=0$ is a real number</p>\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "<p>The complex roots of the equation $P(z)=0$ come in conjugate pairs.</p>\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "<p>All the roots cannot be real</p>"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "D"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>Given : $P(z)=z^3+(1+j) z^2+(2+j) z+3$</p>\n<p>For standard $3^{\\text {rd }}$ order equation of the from</p>\n<p>$$ \\alpha x^3+\\beta x^2+\\gamma x+\\delta=0 $$</p>\n<p>If the roots are $a, b$ and $c$ then</p>\n<p>Sum of roots $a+b+c=\\frac{-\\beta}{\\alpha}$</p>\n<p>Product of roots $a \\cdot b=\\frac{-\\delta}{\\alpha}$</p>\n<p>and $a b+b c+c a=\\frac{\\gamma}{\\alpha}$</p>\n<p>For given equation,</p>\n<p>$$ a+b+c=\\frac{-\\beta}{\\alpha}=\\frac{-(1+j)}{1}=-(1+j) $$</p>\n<p>Hence all the roots cannot be real.</p>\n<p>$$ a \\cdot b \\cdot c=\\frac{-\\delta}{\\alpha}=\\frac{-3}{1}=-3 $$</p>\n<p>Complex roots can't be conjugate because sum of complex conjugate roots must be real. Hence, the correct option is (D).</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2021,
    "yearKey": "gate-ee-2021",
    "difficulty": null
  },
